{"title_page": "Stephen K. Amos", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2013}}\n{{BLP refimprove|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name        = Stephen K. Amos\n| image       = Stephenkamos.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = Amos at the [[Edinburgh Fringe Festival]] in 2005\n| pseudonym   =\n| birth_name  = Stephen Kehinde Amos\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1967|12|3|df=yes}}<ref name=\"facebook.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/stephenkamos/posts/10153377148827991|title=Stephen K Amos|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[London]], England\n| medium      = [[Stand-up comedy|Stand up]], television\n| nationality = British\n| active      =\n| genre       = [[Observational comedy]], political satire\n| subject     = Australian culture, British culture, Nigerian culture, current events, sex, popular culture, human interaction, racism\n| influenced  =\n| spouse      =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| emmyawards  =\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Kehinde Amos''' (born 3 December 1967)<ref name=\"murder\">{{cite news|last1=Iqbal|first1=Nosheen|title=Stephen K Amos: Murder, he wrote|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2009/dec/01/stephen-k-amos-comedian|work=The Guardian|date=2 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"facebook.com\"/> is a British [[stand-up comedian]]<ref name=\"theage.com.au\">{{cite news |first=Stephanie |last=Bunbury |title=Black, gay and game for a laugh |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2008/09/21/1221935446966.html?page=2 |work=The Age |date=22 September 2008 |accessdate=2 December 2009 |quote=[Amos] recalled the moment when he realised he was attracted to men.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Steve |last=Bennett |title=Stephen K Amos: All Of Me |url=http://old.chortle.co.uk/edfest2006/edshows.html?http&&&old.chortle.co.uk/edfest2006/stephenk.htm |work=Chortle |date=August 2006 |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Anna |last=Lozynski |title= Stephen K Amos |url=http://www.australianstage.com.au/reviews/melbourne/stephen-k-amos-275.html |work=Australian Stage |date=7 April 2007 |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref> and television personality. A regular on the international comedy circuit, he is known for including his audience members during his shows. He began his career as a [[Master of Ceremonies|compere]] at the Big Fish comedy clubs in South London, and has been nominated for [[Chortle]]'s Best Compere Award three times in 2004, 2007 and 2008.\n\n==Performances and tours==\nHe has performed stand up at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] every year since [[2003 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2003]], after making his d\u00e9but in [[2001 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2001]]. During the [[2006 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2006 Fringe]], he performed the revealing solo show ''All of Me'', in which he publicly acknowledged his own [[homosexuality]] to his audience for the first time.\n\nHe hosted a chat show on weekends (in addition to his own show), performed as a guest at various extra festival shows, such as ''Spank!'', and performed daily in [[Stewart Lee]]'s production of [[Eric Bogosian]]'s play ''[[Talk Radio (play)|Talk Radio]]''. Away from the fringe, Amos is a regular performer at [[The Comedy Store, London]], featuring on the bill several evenings each month, as well as various other venues around central London.\n\nAmos appeared in the winning team at the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]]'s Great Debate in 2006, 2007, and 2008 for the negative team, and in 2009 for the affirmative team. In May 2007, he appeared at the New Zealand International Comedy festival where he won the award for Best International Comedian. He performed at the 2007 ''Class Clowns State Final'' in [[South Australia]].\n\nDuring the end of 2008 and the beginning of 2009, he embarked on a United Kingdom tour of his show ''Find the Funny''. In the winter of 2009 and 2010, he sold out his second national tour ''The Feelgood Factor''. In 2012 and 2013, he performed his ''Laughter Is My Agenda'' tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edinburgh-reviews.co.uk/review-of-stephen-k-amos-work-in-progress/|title=Review of Stephen K Amos: Work in Progress, Fringe 2012|date=2012-08-10|website=Edinburgh Reviews|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\nAs an actor, he performed in both the Edinburgh Fringe and London run of a version of ''[[One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (play)|One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest]]''. His debut DVD was released in November 2009 entitled ''Find The Funny \u2013 Live''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen K Amos: Find The Funny |url=http://www.play.com/DVD/DVD/4-/11315742/Stephen-K-Amos-Find-The-Funny/Product.html |publisher=Play.com (UK) |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref> His second DVD was released in November 2010 entitled ''The Feelgood Factor''.\n\nIn April 2010, Amos hosted [[The People's Music Awards]] in London.\n\nAmos hosted, and performed a short set on the main stage at London's Gay Pride parade on 3 June 2010. Amos performed on the alternative stage at [[Reading and Leeds Festivals|Reading Festival]] on 27 August 2010, and the Leeds Festival on 28 August 2010. He received a standing ovation for both performances. In March 2017, Amos featured on the 339th episode of the podcast based in Melbourne, ''The Little Dum Dum Club'', which was recorded live at the European Bier Cafe in Melbourne's CBD.\n\n==Television appearances==\nIn his native United Kingdom, Amos has appeared as a guest on panel shows such as ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'', ''[[Mock the Week]]'', ''[[The Wright Stuff]]'' and ''[[And Then You Die (TV series)|And Then You Die]]''. In March 2007, his documentary on [[homophobia]] in the black British community and Jamaica, ''Batty Man'', was broadcast by [[Channel 4]]. It won a Royal Television Society Award and was nominated for a BAFTA.\n\nHe appeared in ''[[The Bill]]'' ('Compliments of the Service') in 1993. He made a guest appearance as [[Jimi Hendrix]] on the third episode of the BBC Three show, ''[[Snuff Box]]''. He has also appeared in [[Rich Hall]]'s ''Cattle Drive'', ''[[EastEnders]]'', ''[[Stewart Lee's Comedy Vehicle]]'' and as a featured performer on [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Live at the Apollo (TV series)|Live at the Apollo]]'' after [[Dara \u00d3 Briain]] and before [[Frankie Boyle]]. In December 2010, Amos appeared on ''Live at the Apollo'' as host and compere.\n\nAmos has the distinction of being one of the few stand up comics chosen to appear at the 2007 [[Royal Variety Performance]]. Amos made an appearance on the gala/comedy gig ''We Are Most Amused'', an [[ITV1]] televised production on 15 November 2008, in celebration of [[The Prince of Wales]]' 60th Birthday. The event took place in the [[New Wimbledon Theatre]].\n\nIn December 2007, he hosted a documentary, ''[[....Envy|Penis Envy]]'',<ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Whitelaw |title=Overexposure of a sensitive area |url=http://living.scotsman.com/tvradio/Overexposure-of-a-sensitive-area.3587832.jp |work=The Scotsman |date=7 December 2007 |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.virginmedia.com/tvradio/virgin1/penis-envy.php |title=Penis Envy |publisher=Virgin Media |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref> for the free United Kingdom digital television channel [[Virgin1]],<ref>{{cite pressrelease|url=http://www.virginmediatv.co.uk/news.php?articleID=103 |title=Virgin 1's brand new cock-umentary gets to grips with The Great British Penis |publisher=Virgin Media Television |date=30 September 2007 |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref> in which he explored men's ongoing insecurities with penis size with the help of actors from ''[[Puppetry of the Penis]]'', naked rugby players and the men willing to experiment with apparent [[Penis enlargement|penis enlarging]] \"treatments\". On a related note, he gently mocks political correctness, in one of his favourite recurring jokes referring to his own penis size: \"some stereotypes I can live with!\"\n\nWhile in Australia for the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]], Amos often appears on Australian television shows such as the improvisational ''[[Thank God You're Here]]''; the music-based panel game show ''[[Spicks and Specks (TV series)|Spicks and Specks]]''; and satirical news based comedy quiz show ''[[Good News Week]]''.\n\nIn 2009, Stephen appeared on ''[[Soccer AM]]'', and is a fan of [[West Ham United]]. In 2009, Stephen also appeared on an edition of [[Children in Need]] of ''[[Mastermind (TV series)|Mastermind]]'', answering questions on the band [[Five Star]].<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00p1g76 Mastermind Special] BBC Children In Need 2009</ref> In March 2010, Amos appeared with the [[England national rugby union team|England rugby squad]] playing [[Nelson Mandela]], in an comedy sketch for the BBC's ''[[Sport Relief]]''.\n\nIn January 2010, he was a celebrity guest team captain on ''[[What Do Kids Know?]]'' along with [[Rufus Hound]], [[Joe Swash]] and [[Sara Cox]] on [[Watch (TV channel)|Watch]]. Stephen guest appeared in Series 2, Episode 7 of the [[BBC Three]] comedy, ''[[Coming of Age (BBC TV series)|Coming of Age]]'' and as a guest contributor on several episodes of ''[[This Week (BBC TV series)|This Week]]''.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/this_week/7700556.stm BBC This Week: Amos, O'Rourke, Kat Von D and Moore]. BBC News (28 April 2011). Retrieved 25 March 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Amos's own show was launched, a combination of stand up, sketches, and guest performers (who for the most part had not fully broken into television comedy), simply entitled ''The Stephen K Amos Show''. The show was released on DVD in November 2010. In 2010, for the show ''[[Tinga Tinga Tales]]'' Amos voiced the characters [[Hyena]] and [[Millipede]]/Pediless. Amos also starred in an episode of ''[[Mad Mad World (TV Series)|Mad Mad World]]'' on [[ITV1]] in Spring 2012.\n\nIn January 2013, he took part in a special series of ''[[The Great British Bake Off]]''.\n\nIn 2019, Amos starred in BBC's Pilgrimage show<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09w7lc0|title=\"Pilgrimage|last=|first=|date=|website=BBC|access-date=24 December 2019}}</ref>, walking [[Via Francigena]], an ancient [[Christian_pilgrimage|pilgrimage]] route to Rome. Amos told [[Pope Francis]] \"As a gay man, I don't feel accepted\". \nThe Pope responded, \"Giving more importance to the adjective rather than the noun, this is not good. We are all human beings and have dignity. It does not matter who you are or how you live your life, you do not lose your dignity. There are people that prefer to select or discard people because of the adjective - these people don't have a human heart.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/pilgrimage-road-to-rome-pope-meeting-lgbt-gay-rights-stephen-k-amos-bbc-what-time-date-final-503422|title=\"Stephen K Amos: 'I refused to meet the Pope unless I could ask him about LGBT rights'|last=|first=|date=|website=iNews|access-date=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Radio appearances==\nOn 2 November 2008, Amos appeared on ''[[The Jon Richardson Show]]'' on [[BBC 6 Music]], and again on 16 August 2009 and 23 November 2009. Amos also appeared on [[Nihal (DJ)|Nihal]]'s Saturday Afternoon Show on [[BBC Radio One]] on 30 May 2009. Amos is currently featured in the [[BBC Radio 4]] show ''The Odd Half Hour'', which began broadcasting on 16 November 2010.\n\nIn 2012 Amos chaired a BBC Radio 4 programme, called ''[[Life: An Idiot's Guide]]'', starting March 2012, where he and his pick of the circuit's best stand ups build an idiot's guide to life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01d2ft3 |title=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 Life: An Idiot's Guide, Series 1 |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=4 April 2012 |accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nPeople who have appeared on the show include [[Lucy Montgomery (actor)|Lucy Montgomery]] and [[Lucy Porter]]. In February 2013, Amos presented another series of this programme, where guests on the programme included [[Fred MacAulay]], [[Angela Barnes]] and [[Greg Proops]]. Since December 2013, Amos has also appeared in a purportedly autobiographical radio comedy series ''[[What Does the K Stand For?]]'' on BBC Radio 4, as a son living in a Nigerian family in 1980s Britain.\n\nThe series is co written by [[Jonathan Harvey (playwright)|Jonathan Harvey]], and the third series commenced in January 2017.<ref name=\"Series 3 Episode 1\">{{cite episode| title= Working for a Living| episodelink= | series= What Does the K Stand For?| credits= Writers: [[Jonathan Harvey (playwright)|Jonathan Harvey]], Stephen K. Amos; Producer: Paul Sheehan| network= BBC| station= [[BBC Radio Four]]| url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08bb33b| airdate= 25 January 2017| accessdate= 1 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''I Used To Say My Mother Was Shirley Bassey'' (Constable, London, 2012)\n\n==Personal life==\nAmos, one of eight children, lives in [[South London]]. His parents came to London from Nigeria in the 1960s.<ref name=\"theage.com.au\"/> On [[Fern Britton]]'s ''[[The 5 O'Clock Show]]'' (Channel 4, 19 July 2010), he stated that his middle name is [[Kehinde]], which is a [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]] name for \"second of twins\". Amos had an older twin sister, who died in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen K Amos Interview. The comedian in conversation in 2018. |url=https://www.on-magazine.co.uk/interview/celebrity/stephen-k-amos/ |website=On: Yorkshire Magazine {{!}} Yorkshire's Online Publication |accessdate=18 April 2019 |date=4 November 2018}}</ref> He studied [[criminal justice]] at the [[University of Westminster|Polytechnic of Central London]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Randall|first1=Lee|title=Interview: Stephen K Amos, comedian and author|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/interview-stephen-k-amos-comedian-and-author-1-2542952|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=24 September 2012}}</ref>  He is [[gay]] and an [[atheist]].<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2010/oct/24/stephen-k-amos-interview | title= Stephen K Amos: 'I don't want to be labelled \"the black gay comic\"' | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Stephanie | last=Merritt | date=31 October 2010 | accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref><ref>https://nypost.com/2019/04/19/pope-anyone-who-discards-gay-people-doesnt-have-a-human-heart/</ref>\n\nAmos is a celebrity supporter of the [[British Red Cross]], where he is interested in their work with refugees.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stephen K Amos |url=http://www.redcross.org.uk/standard.asp?id=79469 |publisher=British Red Cross |access-date=2 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217215557/http://www.redcross.org.uk/standard.asp?id=79469 |archive-date=17 February 2009 }}</ref> Amos is a member of [[The Arts Emergency Service]].<ref>[http://www.4thought.tv/themes/is-anything-sacred-in-comedy/stephen-k-amos All 4]. 4thought.tv (12 February 2016). Retrieved 25 March 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://e-activist.com/ea-action/action?ea.client.id=1789&ea.campaign.id=23045|title=Media Diversity UK|publisher=E-activist.com |date= |accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Stand up DVDs==\n*''Find the Funny'' (23 November 2009)\n*''The Feel Good Factor'' (15 November 2010)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1510030}}\n*[http://www.chortle.co.uk/comics/s/200/stephen_k_amos Chortle profile]\n*[http://www.theedinburghblog.co.uk/edinburgh-festivals/stephen-k-amos-more-of-me-edinburgh-festival-fringe-review/08-19-2007/index.html Review of Stephen K Amos at the Edinburgh Festival Fringe 2007]\n*''[http://www.channel4learning.com/support/programmenotes/micro/battyman/index.html Batty Man]'' \u2013 Channel 4\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amos, Stephen K.}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Black English people]]\n[[Category:Black English comedians]]\n[[Category:Comedians from London]]\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:English people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT comedians]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from England]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gay entertainers]]\n[[Category:English atheists]]\n[[Category:English people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Yoruba comedians]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century English comedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2013}}\n{{BLP refimprove|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name        = Stephen K. Amos\n| image       = Stephenkamos.jpg\n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = Amos at the [[Edinburgh Fringe Festival]] in 2005\n| pseudonym   =\n| birth_name  = Stephen Kehinde Amos\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1967|12|3|df=yes}}<ref name=\"facebook.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/stephenkamos/posts/10153377148827991|title=Stephen K Amos|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[London]], England\n| medium      = [[Stand-up comedy|Stand up]], television\n| nationality = British\n| active      =\n| genre       = [[Observational comedy]], political satire\n| subject     = Australian culture, British culture, Nigerian culture, current events, sex, popular culture, human interaction, racism\n| influenced  =\n| spouse      =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| emmyawards  =\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Kehinde Amos''' (born 3 December 1967)<ref name=\"murder\">{{cite news|last1=Iqbal|first1=Nosheen|title=Stephen K Amos: Murder, he wrote|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2009/dec/01/stephen-k-amos-comedian|work=The Guardian|date=2 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"facebook.com\"/> is a British [[stand-up comedian]]<ref name=\"theage.com.au\">{{cite news |first=Stephanie |last=Bunbury |title=Black, gay and game for a laugh |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2008/09/21/1221935446966.html?page=2 |work=The Age |date=22 September 2008 |accessdate=2 December 2009 |quote=[Amos] recalled the moment when he realised he was attracted to men.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Steve |last=Bennett |title=Stephen K Amos: All Of Me |url=http://old.chortle.co.uk/edfest2006/edshows.html?http&&&old.chortle.co.uk/edfest2006/stephenk.htm |work=Chortle |date=August 2006 |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Anna |last=Lozynski |title= Stephen K Amos |url=http://www.australianstage.com.au/reviews/melbourne/stephen-k-amos-275.html |work=Australian Stage |date=7 April 2007 |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref> and television personality. A regular on the international comedy circuit, he is known for including his audience members during his shows. He began his career as a [[Master of Ceremonies|compere]] at the Big Fish comedy clubs in South London, and has been nominated for [[Chortle]]'s Best Compere Award three times in 2004, 2007 and 2008.\n\n==Performances and tours==\nHe has performed stand up at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] every year since [[2003 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2003]], after making his d\u00e9but in [[2001 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2001]]. During the [[2006 Edinburgh Festival Fringe|2006 Fringe]], he performed the revealing solo show ''All of Me'', in which he publicly acknowledged his own [[homosexuality]] to his audience for the first time.\n\nHe hosted a chat show on weekends (in addition to his own show), performed as a guest at various extra festival shows, such as ''Spank!'', and performed daily in [[Stewart Lee]]'s production of [[Eric Bogosian]]'s play ''[[Talk Radio (play)|Talk Radio]]''. Away from the fringe, Amos is a regular performer at [[The Comedy Store, London]], featuring on the bill several evenings each month, as well as various other venues around central London.\n\nAmos appeared in the winning team at the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]]'s Great Debate in 2006, 2007, and 2008 for the negative team, and in 2009 for the affirmative team. In May 2007, he appeared at the New Zealand International Comedy festival where he won the award for Best International Comedian. He performed at the 2007 ''Class Clowns State Final'' in [[South Australia]].\n\nDuring the end of 2008 and the beginning of 2009, he embarked on a United Kingdom tour of his show ''Find the Funny''. In the winter of 2009 and 2010, he sold out his second national tour ''The Feelgood Factor''. In 2012 and 2013, he performed his ''Laughter Is My Agenda'' tour<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edinburgh-reviews.co.uk/review-of-stephen-k-amos-work-in-progress/|title=Review of Stephen K Amos: Work in Progress, Fringe 2012|date=2012-08-10|website=Edinburgh Reviews|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>.\n\nAs an actor, he performed in both the Edinburgh Fringe and London run of a version of ''[[One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (play)|One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest]]''. His debut DVD was released in November 2009 entitled ''Find The Funny \u2013 Live''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen K Amos: Find The Funny |url=http://www.play.com/DVD/DVD/4-/11315742/Stephen-K-Amos-Find-The-Funny/Product.html |publisher=Play.com (UK) |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref> His second DVD was released in November 2010 entitled ''The Feelgood Factor''.\n\nIn April 2010, Amos hosted [[The People's Music Awards]] in London.\n\nAmos hosted, and performed a short set on the main stage at London's Gay Pride parade on 3 June 2010. Amos performed on the alternative stage at [[Reading and Leeds Festivals|Reading Festival]] on 27 August 2010, and the Leeds Festival on 28 August 2010. He received a standing ovation for both performances. In March 2017, Amos featured on the 339th episode of the podcast based in Melbourne, ''The Little Dum Dum Club'', which was recorded live at the European Bier Cafe in Melbourne's CBD.\n\n==Television appearances==\nIn his native United Kingdom, Amos has appeared as a guest on panel shows such as ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'', ''[[Mock the Week]]'', ''[[The Wright Stuff]]'' and ''[[And Then You Die (TV series)|And Then You Die]]''. In March 2007, his documentary on [[homophobia]] in the black British community and Jamaica, ''Batty Man'', was broadcast by [[Channel 4]]. It won a Royal Television Society Award and was nominated for a BAFTA.\n\nHe appeared in ''[[The Bill]]'' ('Compliments of the Service') in 1993. He made a guest appearance as [[Jimi Hendrix]] on the third episode of the BBC Three show, ''[[Snuff Box]]''. He has also appeared in [[Rich Hall]]'s ''Cattle Drive'', ''[[EastEnders]]'', ''[[Stewart Lee's Comedy Vehicle]]'' and as a featured performer on [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Live at the Apollo (TV series)|Live at the Apollo]]'' after [[Dara \u00d3 Briain]] and before [[Frankie Boyle]]. In December 2010, Amos appeared on ''Live at the Apollo'' as host and compere.\n\nAmos has the distinction of being one of the few stand up comics chosen to appear at the 2007 [[Royal Variety Performance]]. Amos made an appearance on the gala/comedy gig ''We Are Most Amused'', an [[ITV1]] televised production on 15 November 2008, in celebration of [[The Prince of Wales]]' 60th Birthday. The event took place in the [[New Wimbledon Theatre]].\n\nIn December 2007, he hosted a documentary, ''[[....Envy|Penis Envy]]'',<ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Whitelaw |title=Overexposure of a sensitive area |url=http://living.scotsman.com/tvradio/Overexposure-of-a-sensitive-area.3587832.jp |work=The Scotsman |date=7 December 2007 |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.virginmedia.com/tvradio/virgin1/penis-envy.php |title=Penis Envy |publisher=Virgin Media |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref> for the free United Kingdom digital television channel [[Virgin1]],<ref>{{cite pressrelease|url=http://www.virginmediatv.co.uk/news.php?articleID=103 |title=Virgin 1's brand new cock-umentary gets to grips with The Great British Penis |publisher=Virgin Media Television |date=30 September 2007 |accessdate=2 December 2009}}</ref> in which he explored men's ongoing insecurities with penis size with the help of actors from ''[[Puppetry of the Penis]]'', naked rugby players and the men willing to experiment with apparent [[Penis enlargement|penis enlarging]] \"treatments\". On a related note, he gently mocks political correctness, in one of his favourite recurring jokes referring to his own penis size: \"some stereotypes I can live with!\"\n\nWhile in Australia for the [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]], Amos often appears on Australian television shows such as the improvisational ''[[Thank God You're Here]]''; the music-based panel game show ''[[Spicks and Specks (TV series)|Spicks and Specks]]''; and satirical news based comedy quiz show ''[[Good News Week]]''.\n\nIn 2009, Stephen appeared on ''[[Soccer AM]]'', and is a fan of [[West Ham United]]. In 2009, Stephen also appeared on an edition of [[Children in Need]] of ''[[Mastermind (TV series)|Mastermind]]'', answering questions on the band [[Five Star]].<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00p1g76 Mastermind Special] BBC Children In Need 2009</ref> In March 2010, Amos appeared with the [[England national rugby union team|England rugby squad]] playing [[Nelson Mandela]], in an comedy sketch for the BBC's ''[[Sport Relief]]''.\n\nIn January 2010, he was a celebrity guest team captain on ''[[What Do Kids Know?]]'' along with [[Rufus Hound]], [[Joe Swash]] and [[Sara Cox]] on [[Watch (TV channel)|Watch]]. Stephen guest appeared in Series 2, Episode 7 of the [[BBC Three]] comedy, ''[[Coming of Age (BBC TV series)|Coming of Age]]'' and as a guest contributor on several episodes of ''[[This Week (BBC TV series)|This Week]]''.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/this_week/7700556.stm BBC This Week: Amos, O'Rourke, Kat Von D and Moore]. BBC News (28 April 2011). Retrieved 25 March 2016.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Amos's own show was launched, a combination of stand up, sketches, and guest performers (who for the most part had not fully broken into television comedy), simply entitled ''The Stephen K Amos Show''. The show was released on DVD in November 2010. In 2010, for the show ''[[Tinga Tinga Tales]]'' Amos voiced the characters [[Hyena]] and [[Millipede]]/Pediless. Amos also starred in an episode of ''[[Mad Mad World (TV Series)|Mad Mad World]]'' on [[ITV1]] in Spring 2012.\n\nIn January 2013, he took part in a special series of ''[[The Great British Bake Off]]''.\n\nIn 2019, Amos starred in BBC's Pilgrimage show<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09w7lc0|title=\"Pilgrimage|last=|first=|date=|website=BBC|access-date=24 December 2019}}</ref>, walking [[Via Francigena]], an ancient [[Christian_pilgrimage|pilgrimage]] route to Rome. Amos told [[Pope Francis]] \"As a gay man, I don't feel accepted\". \nThe Pope responded, \"Giving more importance to the adjective rather than the noun, this is not good. We are all human beings and have dignity. It does not matter who you are or how you live your life, you do not lose your dignity. There are people that prefer to select or discard people because of the adjective - these people don't have a human heart.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/pilgrimage-road-to-rome-pope-meeting-lgbt-gay-rights-stephen-k-amos-bbc-what-time-date-final-503422|title=\"Stephen K Amos: 'I refused to meet the Pope unless I could ask him about LGBT rights'|last=|first=|date=|website=iNews|access-date=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Radio appearances==\nOn 2 November 2008, Amos appeared on ''[[The Jon Richardson Show]]'' on [[BBC 6 Music]], and again on 16 August 2009 and 23 November 2009. Amos also appeared on [[Nihal (DJ)|Nihal]]'s Saturday Afternoon Show on [[BBC Radio One]] on 30 May 2009. Amos is currently featured in the [[BBC Radio 4]] show ''The Odd Half Hour'', which began broadcasting on 16 November 2010.\n\nIn 2012 Amos chaired a BBC Radio 4 programme, called ''[[Life: An Idiot's Guide]]'', starting March 2012, where he and his pick of the circuit's best stand ups build an idiot's guide to life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01d2ft3 |title=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 Life: An Idiot's Guide, Series 1 |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=4 April 2012 |accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nPeople who have appeared on the show include [[Lucy Montgomery (actor)|Lucy Montgomery]] and [[Lucy Porter]]. In February 2013, Amos presented another series of this programme, where guests on the programme included [[Fred MacAulay]], [[Angela Barnes]] and [[Greg Proops]]. Since December 2013, Amos has also appeared in a purportedly autobiographical radio comedy series ''[[What Does the K Stand For?]]'' on BBC Radio 4, as a son living in a Nigerian family in 1980s Britain.\n\nThe series is co written by [[Jonathan Harvey (playwright)|Jonathan Harvey]], and the third series commenced in January 2017.<ref name=\"Series 3 Episode 1\">{{cite episode| title= Working for a Living| episodelink= | series= What Does the K Stand For?| credits= Writers: [[Jonathan Harvey (playwright)|Jonathan Harvey]], Stephen K. Amos; Producer: Paul Sheehan| network= BBC| station= [[BBC Radio Four]]| url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08bb33b| airdate= 25 January 2017| accessdate= 1 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''I Used To Say My Mother Was Shirley Bassey'' (Constable, London, 2012)\n\n==Personal life==\nAmos, one of eight children, lives in [[South London]]. His parents came to London from Nigeria in the 1960s.<ref name=\"theage.com.au\"/> On [[Fern Britton]]'s ''[[The 5 O'Clock Show]]'' (Channel 4, 19 July 2010), he stated that his middle name is [[Kehinde]], which is a [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]] name for \"second of twins\". Amos had an older twin sister, who died in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen K Amos Interview. The comedian in conversation in 2018. |url=https://www.on-magazine.co.uk/interview/celebrity/stephen-k-amos/ |website=On: Yorkshire Magazine {{!}} Yorkshire's Online Publication |accessdate=18 April 2019 |date=4 November 2018}}</ref> He studied [[criminal justice]] at the [[University of Westminster|Polytechnic of Central London]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Randall|first1=Lee|title=Interview: Stephen K Amos, comedian and author|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/interview-stephen-k-amos-comedian-and-author-1-2542952|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=24 September 2012}}</ref>  He is [[gay]] and an [[atheist]].<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2010/oct/24/stephen-k-amos-interview | title= Stephen K Amos: 'I don't want to be labelled \"the black gay comic\"' | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Stephanie | last=Merritt | date=31 October 2010 | accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref><ref>https://nypost.com/2019/04/19/pope-anyone-who-discards-gay-people-doesnt-have-a-human-heart/</ref>\n\nAmos is a celebrity supporter of the [[British Red Cross]], where he is interested in their work with refugees.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stephen K Amos |url=http://www.redcross.org.uk/standard.asp?id=79469 |publisher=British Red Cross |access-date=2 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217215557/http://www.redcross.org.uk/standard.asp?id=79469 |archive-date=17 February 2009 }}</ref> Amos is a member of [[The Arts Emergency Service]].<ref>[http://www.4thought.tv/themes/is-anything-sacred-in-comedy/stephen-k-amos All 4]. 4thought.tv (12 February 2016). Retrieved 25 March 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://e-activist.com/ea-action/action?ea.client.id=1789&ea.campaign.id=23045|title=Media Diversity UK|publisher=E-activist.com |date= |accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Stand up DVDs==\n*''Find the Funny'' (23 November 2009)\n*''The Feel Good Factor'' (15 November 2010)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1510030}}\n*[http://www.chortle.co.uk/comics/s/200/stephen_k_amos Chortle profile]\n*[http://www.theedinburghblog.co.uk/edinburgh-festivals/stephen-k-amos-more-of-me-edinburgh-festival-fringe-review/08-19-2007/index.html Review of Stephen K Amos at the Edinburgh Festival Fringe 2007]\n*''[http://www.channel4learning.com/support/programmenotes/micro/battyman/index.html Batty Man]'' \u2013 Channel 4\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amos, Stephen K.}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Westminster]]\n[[Category:Black English people]]\n[[Category:Black English comedians]]\n[[Category:Comedians from London]]\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:English people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT comedians]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from England]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gay entertainers]]\n[[Category:English atheists]]\n[[Category:English people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:Yoruba comedians]]\n[[Category:Twin people from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century English comedians]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_K._Amos"}
{"title_page": "The Muppets (TV series)", "text_new": "{{about||the 1976 TV series|The Muppet Show|the 2011 film|The Muppets (film)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Muppets\n| image                    = The Muppets (TV) title card.jpg\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = {{Plain list|\n*[[Sitcom]]\n*[[Mockumentary]]\n*[[Puppetry]]\n}}\n| developer                = {{Plain list|\n*[[Bill Prady]]\n*[[Bob Kushell]]\n}}\n| based_on                 = {{Based on|[[List of Muppets|Characters]]|[[Jim Henson]]}}<!--[[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]'s [[The Muppets|Muppet properties]] and [[List of Muppets|characters]] created by [[Jim Henson]]-->\n| executive_producer       = {{Plain list|\n*Bill Prady\n*Bob Kushell\n*Kristin Newman\n*Randall Einhorn\n*[[Bill Barretta]]\n*Kyle Laughlin\n*Debbie McClellan\n}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Randall Einhorn]]\n* Matt Sohn\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n*Margee Magee\n*Angeli Millan\n*Kris Eber\n*Emily Wilson\n}}\n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Steve Whitmire]]\n*[[Eric Jacobson]]\n*[[Dave Goelz]]\n*[[Bill Barretta]]\n*[[David Rudman]]\n*[[Matt Vogel (puppeteer)|Matt Vogel]]\n*[[Peter Linz]]\n}}\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 16\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| runtime                  = 22 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n*[[ABC Studios]]\n*[[The Muppets Studio]]\n*Bill Prady Productions\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n| opentheme                = \"Opening Theme\" by Dave Thomas Jr. (includes \"[[The Muppet Show Theme]]\" by Jim Henson and [[Sam Pottle]])<ref name=VultureRecap2/>\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n*Ed Mitchell\n*Steve Morrell\n}}\n| channel                  = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| location                 = \n| picture_format           = [[720p]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])<ref name=\"futon1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings.aspx?id=20150908abc01|title=Go Behind the Scenes With Kermit and the Gang as They Produce a Late Night Talk Show on the Series Premiere of \"THE MUPPETS\"|work=The Futon Critic|date=September 8, 2015|accessdate=September 9, 2015}}</ref>\n| audio_format             = [[5.1 surround sound]]<ref name=\"futon1\"/>\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2015|9|22}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2016|3|1}}\n| website                  = http://abc.go.com/shows/the-muppets\n}}\n'''''The Muppets''''' (stylized as '''''the muppets.''''') is an American [[television comedy]] series that originally aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] from September 22, 2015 to March 1, 2016. Co-created by [[Bill Prady]] and [[Bob Kushell]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hibbard |first1=James |title=The Muppets Revival Greenlit as First Photo Released |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/05/07/muppets-abc-greenlit |accessdate=May 9, 2015 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=May 7, 2015}}</ref> the series was produced by [[ABC Studios]] and [[The Muppets Studio]], with [[Randall Einhorn]] and Muppet performer [[Bill Barretta]] serving as executive producers alongside Prady and Kushell.<ref name=\"Muppets Revival\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/abc-orders-794296 |title=ABC Orders Shondaland and Jenna Bans Dramas, 'Muppets' Revival, More |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 7, 2015 |accessdate=May 8, 2015}}</ref> On May 12, 2016, ABC canceled the series after one season.\n\nThe series is set in [[Los Angeles]] and depicts the everyday personal and professional lives of [[The Muppets]] during production of ''Up Late with Miss Piggy'', a fictional [[late-night talk show]] starring [[Miss Piggy]] airing on ABC after ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''<ref name=\"VarietyComicCon\">{{cite news |last1=Wagmeister |first1=Elizabeth |title='The Muppets' Woo Over Comic-Con; Kermit & Miss Piggy Reveal ABC Series Details |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/the-muppets-abc-comic-con-panel-1201538499/ |accessdate=July 12, 2015 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=July 11, 2015}}</ref> ''The Muppets'' serves as a [[parody]] of other [[mockumentary]]-style series, such as ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', ''[[Modern Family]]'', and ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' by employing the same [[single-camera setup]] filming style with the implication of a documentary crew filming everyone.<ref name=NYTProd/> The series stars Muppet performers [[Steve Whitmire]], [[Eric Jacobson]], [[Dave Goelz]], Bill Barretta, [[David Rudman]], [[Matt Vogel (puppeteer)|Matt Vogel]], and [[Peter Linz]] in multiple roles.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Zeitchik|first1=Steven|title=ABC's 'Muppets' takes Kermit and Co. out into the real world -- will they remain subtly subversive?|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-ca-st-fall-tv-muppets-20150913-story.html|accessdate=September 11, 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|date=September 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe series marks the characters' first ongoing prime-time network television series since ''[[Muppets Tonight]]'' was canceled in 1998. ''The Muppets'' was picked up by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], the same network that aired ''Muppets Tonight''\u2014as the characters, the network, and the production companies are all owned by [[The Walt Disney Company]]\u2014on the ABC network schedule.\n\nThis marks the second time Prady has attempted to revive The Muppets. Before co-creating [[CBS]]' ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'', the writer-producer shot some test footage on which ABC ultimately passed. Prady's history with The Muppets dates back to his work on ''[[Fraggle Rock]]'' in 1987. His previous writing credits for Muppet productions include the ''[[Muppet*Vision 3D]]'' attraction at [[Walt Disney World]], and the tribute special ''[[The Muppets Celebrate Jim Henson]]'', which earned Prady an [[Emmy Award]] nomination in 1991.<ref name=\"Muppets Revival\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Jim Henson Remembered: \u2018Muppets\u2019 Producer Bill Prady Pays Tribute to His Legendary Mentor|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/jim-henson-muppets-big-bang-theory-bill-prady-1201496535/|accessdate=September 18, 2015|work=Variety|date=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nExecutive producer Bob Kushell explained the intention behind the series; \"We have the opportunity to explore these characters as individuals with their own emotional lives that are separate from each other and aren't shadowed by each other's presence, as I think they have been for the last 20 years... it's not just a behind-the-scenes look at a show, but it's the relationship-driven, emotional stories that people go through in their personal lives. Everyone in this version of The Muppets wants to push them further in a way they've never been before.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Snetiker|first1=Marc|title=A day on set with Piggy, Kermit, and the brand-new Muppets|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/09/11/muppets-behind-the-scenes-kermit-miss-piggy|accessdate=September 11, 2015|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=September 11, 2015}}</ref> Kushell added, \"Rightfully or wrongfully, The Muppets became more of a kids' product over the years. We want to bring them all the way back to what they were intended to be and then some. But never so much that anyone has to explain anything uncomfortable to their kids.\"<ref name=NYTProd/>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{Main|List of Muppets}}\n\n===Main cast===\n* [[Steve Whitmire]] as:\n** [[Kermit the Frog]], the show's [[executive producer]] and Denise's boyfriend.\n** [[Rizzo the Rat]], one of Gonzo's staff writers.<ref name=THRAug15>{{cite news|last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title=ABC's 'Muppets' Will Feature Music, But Not Politics|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/abcs-muppets-will-feature-music-813059|accessdate=August 4, 2015|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=August 4, 2015}}</ref>\n** [[Beaker (Muppet)|Beaker]], Bunsen's frazzled assistant.<ref name=THRAug15 />\n** [[Statler and Waldorf|Statler]], a heckler and audience member of ''Up Late with Miss Piggy''.<ref name=THRAug15 />\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Lips|Lips]], the trumpet player of [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem|The Electric Mayhem]], the show's [[house band]].<ref name=\"HouseBandEW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/09/14/muppets-season-1-study-guide|title=Everything we know about the Muppets revival (so far)|last=Zhu|first=Danielle|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=September 14, 2015|accessdate=September 14, 2015}}</ref>\n** [[List of Muppets#The Muppet Newsman|The Muppet Newsman]], a local news presenter who operates in a nearby studio.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dornbush|first1=Jonathan|title=TV Recaps <nowiki>|</nowiki> The Muppets: 'Hostile Makeover'|url=http://www.ew.com/recap/the-muppets-season-1-episode-2|accessdate=September 30, 2015|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n** [[List of Muppets#Additional characters|Foo-Foo]], Miss Piggy's pet [[Bichon Frise]].<ref name=\"THRNewman\" />\n* [[Eric Jacobson]] as:\n** [[Miss Piggy]], the eponymous host of ''Up Late with Miss Piggy'' and Kermit's former [[significant other]].<ref name=\"VarietyComicCon\"/><ref name=DeadlineComicCon>{{cite news|last1=D'Alessandro|first1=Anthony|title=Gonzo On \u2018The Muppets\u2019 New Show: \"We Don\u2019t Have Deals Yet!\" \u2013 Comic Con|url=http://deadline.com/2015/07/the-muppets-comic-con-abc-1201474386/|accessdate=July 12, 2015|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=July 11, 2015}}</ref>\n** [[Fozzie Bear]], a struggling comedian and Piggy's on-air announcer, sidekick and warm-up comic.<ref name=DeadlineComicCon/>\n** [[Animal (Muppet)|Animal]], the crazed drummer of The Electric Mayhem.<ref name=THRAug15/>\n** [[Sam Eagle]], the head executive of [[Broadcast Standards and Practices|broadcast standards and practices]] for ABC.<ref name=THRAug15/>\n**[[List of Muppets#Marvin Suggs|Marvin Suggs]]\n* [[Dave Goelz]] as:\n** [[Gonzo (Muppet)|Gonzo]], the head writer of the show.<ref name=\"EWComicCon\"/>\n** [[Bunsen Honeydew|Dr. Bunsen Honeydew]], a freelance scientist in charge of the show's special effects and the prop department.<ref name=THRAug15 />\n**[[Statler and Waldorf|Waldorf]], a heckler and audience member of ''Up Late with Miss Piggy''.<ref name=THRAug15 />\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Zoot|Zoot]], the reserved saxophone player of The Electric Mayhem.<ref name=\"HouseBandEW\" />\n** [[List of Muppets#Additional characters|Chip]], an [[Information systems technician|IT technician]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Suddath|first1=Claire|title=Can the man behind television\u2019s biggest sitcom\u2014and his puppet twin\u2014help the Muppets take prime time?|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-09-17/new-muppets-sitcom-looks-to-take-prime-time|accessdate=September 21, 2015|work=Bloomberg Business|date=September 17, 2015}}</ref>\n** [[List of Muppets#Beauregard|Beauregard]], the studio janitor.<ref name=AV />\n* [[Bill Barretta]] as:\n**[[Pepe the King Prawn]], one of Gonzo's [[staff writer]]s.<ref name=THRAug15 /><ref name=\"EWComicCon\"/>\n**[[Rowlf the Dog]], the owner of Rowlf's Tavern, a night bar across the street from the studio.<ref name=THRAug15 />\n**[[List of Muppets#Bobo the Bear|Bobo the Bear]], the show's stage manager.<ref name=THRAug15/>\n**[[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Dr. Teeth|Dr. Teeth]], keyboard player and lead vocalist of The Electric Mayhem.<ref name=\"HouseBandEW\" />\n** The [[Swedish Chef]], a chef who is in charge of the show's [[craft service]]s.<ref name=THRAug15 />\n**[[List of Muppets#Additional characters|Big Mean Carl]], the receptionist for ''Up Late with Miss Piggy''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/recap/the-muppets-series-premiere|title='Pig Girls Don't Cry'|last=Dornbush|first=Jonathon|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=September 22, 2015|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[David Rudman]] as:\n** [[Scooter (Muppet)|Scooter]], the show's [[Talent agent|talent coordinator]] and [[associate producer]].<ref name=\"EWComicCon\">{{cite news|last1=Snetiker|first1=Marc|title=The most genius moments from Kermit and Piggy's magical first Muppets panel at Comic-Con|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/11/comic-con-muppets-panel|accessdate=July 12, 2015|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=July 11, 2015|quote=We have a cast of seven performers,...}}</ref>\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Janice|Janice]], the lead guitar player of The Electric Mayhem.<ref name=\"HouseBandEW\" />\n* [[Matt Vogel (puppeteer)|Matt Vogel]] as:\n**[[List of Muppets#Uncle Deadly|Uncle Deadly]], Miss Piggy's wardrobe supervisor.<ref name=\"TVGuideSep2015\" />\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Floyd Pepper|Floyd Pepper]], the bass player for The Electric Mayhem.<ref name=\"HouseBandEW\" />\n** [[List of Muppets#Sweetums|Sweetums]], the show's [[cue card]] operator.<ref name=\"TVGuideSep2015\">{{cite news|last1=Nguyen|first1=Hanh|title=The Muppets: Where Are They Now?|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/the-muppets-where-are-they-now/|accessdate=September 18, 2015|work=TV Guide|date=September 16, 2015}}</ref>\n** [[List of Muppets#Lew Zealand|Lew Zealand]]<ref name=\"THRNewman\" /><ref name=AV>{{cite news|last1=Caffrey|first1=Dan|title=The Muppets\u2019 flaws are justified, if still slightly jarring|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/muppets-flaws-are-justified-if-still-slightly-jarr-226078|accessdate=September 30, 2015|work=The A.V. Club|date=September 30, 2015}}</ref>\n** [[List of Muppets#Crazy Harry|Crazy Harry]]\n**[[List of Muppets#Camilla the Chicken|Camilla the Chicken]], Gonzo's reunited girlfriend <ref name=\"THRNewman\" />\n**[[List of Muppets#Robin the Frog|Robin the Frog]], Kermit's nephew.\n* [[Peter Linz]] as:\n**[[Walter (Muppet)|Walter]], a fan of the Muppets who only appears in the First Look Presentation.\n** Gloria Estefan, a [[Magellanic penguin]] chick who has a fondness for drinking [[Martini (cocktail)|martinis]]. He was adopted by Miss Piggy during her trip to Argentina and quickly forms a bond with Uncle Deadly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/peterlinzpuppeteer/photos/a.132768816867698.38560.131416453669601/780152985462608|title=Just learned the real Gloria Estefan is now aware of my penguin Gloria Estefan.|last=Linz|first=Peter|publisher=Facebook|date=February 3, 2016|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Recurring cast===\n* [[Julianne Buescher]] as:\n** Denise, a pig who works as a network marketer and is Kermit's girlfriend.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Seitz|first1=Matt|title=The New Muppet Show Recaptures Some of the Original\u2019s Glory|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/09/the-muppets-tv-review.html|accessdate=September 18, 2015|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=September 18, 2015}}</ref>\n** Yolanda Rat, Kermit's assistant who is good friends with Rizzo.<ref name=VultureRecap2>{{cite news|last1=Jaffe|first1=Jenny|title=The Muppets Recap: Josh Groban Is a Douche|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/09/muppets-recap-season-1-episode-2.html#|accessdate=September 30, 2015|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=September 30, 2015}}</ref>\n**Debbie\n* [[Riki Lindhome]] as Becky, Fozzie's human girlfriend. She was previously played by [[Margo Harshman]] in the First Look Presentation.\n* [[Layla Alizada]] as Betty, the Hair and Makeup Specialist at ''Up Late with Miss Piggy''.\n* Nilla Watkins as Kim, the production assistant at ''Up Late with Miss Piggy''.\n* [[June Diane Raphael]] as Lucy Royce, the president of ABC.\n* [[Utkarsh Ambudkar]] as Pizza (pronounced \"Pache\"), a \"branding guru\" who is appointed by the network to re-brand ''Up Late with Miss Piggy''. He previously branded [[Keegan-Michael Key]], [[Jordan Peele]], [[Katy Perry]], some warlord, and others. He is constantly trying to get The Muppets to do what he wants for the show, and will go as far as to sabotage them if they don't.<ref name=\"THRNewman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/muppets-midseason-reboot-changes-853752|title=Classic Sketches, Returning Favorites: Inside 'The Muppets' Midseason Reboot|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 10, 2016|accessdate=February 2, 2016}}</ref> In episode 15, however, Sweetums, Rizzo, Pepe, and a few others reform him.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#98FB98 |overall=6 |title=24 |director=15 |writer=20 |airdate=13 |airdateR={{ref label|Canada Airdate|b|b}} |viewers=9 |country=US |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 0\n|RTitle          = First Look Presentation\n|DirectedBy      = [[Randall Einhorn]]\n|WrittenBy       = [[Bill Prady]] & [[Bob Kushell]]\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|7|21}}\n|Viewers         = --\n|ShortSummary    = The Muppets find out ABC is interested in filming a documentary series about them, but Miss Piggy is not on board forcing Kermit to break the bad news that the show will not air. Meanwhile, Fozzie has to meet his girlfriend Becky's parents who do not approve of her dating a bear.\n\n'''Note''': The 10-minute episode was shown at the ABC upfront at [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] in July 2015. It was posted on [[YouTube]] ten days later, but removed from YouTube once the series premiered.\n\nGuest stars: [[Topher Grace]] as himself, [[Elizabeth Banks]] as herself, [[Margo Harshman]] as Becky, [[Jere Burns]] as Carl, [[Meagen Fay]] as Holly\n\n|LineColor       = 98FB98\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 1\n|Title           = Pig Girls Don't Cry (Pilot)\n|DirectedBy      = Randall Einhorn\n|WrittenBy       = Bill Prady & Bob Kushell\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|9|22}}\n|Viewers         = 9.01<ref name=\"1.01\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/09/23/tuesday-final-ratings-the-voice-ncis-limitless-best-time-ever-adjusted-down/470718/|title=Tuesday Final Ratings: 'The Voice', 'NCIS', 'Limitless' & 'The Muppets' Adjusted Up; 'Best Time Ever' Adjusted Down|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|date=September 23, 2015|work=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=September 23, 2015}}</ref>\n|ShortSummary    = The Muppets tackle some of the show's problems and to find guest stars that Miss Piggy approves of since she does not want Elizabeth Banks. Fozzie tries to get Becky's parents to approve of him even though he is a bear. [[Imagine Dragons]] perform their song \"[[Roots (Imagine Dragons song)|Roots]]\".\n\nGuest stars: [[Elizabeth Banks]] as herself, [[Tracy Anderson]] as herself, [[Tom Bergeron]] as himself, [[Imagine Dragons]] as themselves, [[Riki Lindhome]] as Becky, Meagen Fay as Holly, Jere Burns as Carl\n\n|LineColor       = 98FB98\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 2\n|Title           = Hostile Makeover\n|DirectedBy      = Randall Einhorn\n|WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Bill Prady & Bob Kushell|t=[[Dave Caplan]] & Gregg Mettler}}\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|9|29}}\n|Viewers         = 5.78<ref name=\"1.02\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/09/30/tuesday-final-ratings-the-voice-ncis-adjusted-up-best-time-ever-adjusted-down/474416/|title=Tuesday Final Ratings: 'The Voice' + 'NCIS' Adjusted Up; 'Best Time Ever' Adjusted Down|last=Dixon|first=Dani|work=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=September 30, 2015|accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref>\n|ShortSummary    = Hoping to improve her mood, Kermit sets Miss Piggy up with [[Josh Groban]] only to find Josh has his own ideas for the show. Bobo the Bear attempts to sell cookies for his daughter. Fozzie is invited to a party at [[Jay Leno]]'s house and is tempted to obtain a souvenir of the party where he ends up taking (and accidentally breaking) a candy bowl that was previously owned by [[George Carlin]].\n\nGuest stars: [[Josh Groban]] as himself, [[Laurence Fishburne]] as himself, [[Jay Leno]] as himself, [[Lea Thompson]] as herself, [[Reza Aslan]] as himself\n|LineColor       = 98FB98\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 3\n|Title           = Bear Left Then Bear Write\n|DirectedBy      = Randall Einhorn\n|WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Dave Caplan & Gregg Mettler|t=[[Nell Scovell]] & Steve Rudnick}}\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|10|6}}\n|Viewers         = 4.85<ref name=\"1.03\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/10/07/tuesday-final-ratings-oct-6-2015/477169/|title=Tuesday final ratings: 'The Muppets,' 'NCIS' and 'Scream Queens' adjusted up, 'Flash' and 'iZombie' hold|last=Porter|first=Rick|work=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=October 7, 2015|accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n|ShortSummary    =  Trying to spare Fozzie's feelings after he writes a terrible sketch for the show, Kermit inadvertently convinces him to quit and pursue a career as a screenwriter. Miss Piggy is humiliated when [[Christina Applegate]] plays a prank on her on-air and plans to prank her back with Scooter's help. Gonzo uses [[Liam Hemsworth]]'s picture on a dating website leading to complications when his online girlfriend Debbie wants to meet him in person.\n\nGuest stars: [[Christina Applegate]] as herself, [[Nick Offerman]] as himself, [[Liam Hemsworth]] as himself, Chris Jai Alex as Police Officer\n|LineColor       = 98FB98\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber   = 4\n|Title           = Pig Out\n|DirectedBy      = Randall Einhorn\n|WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Bob Kushell & Dave Caplan|t=Gregg Mettler & Nell Scovell}}\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|10|13}}\n|Viewers         = 4.34<ref name=1.04>{{cite news|last1=Porter|first1=Rick|title=Tuesday final ratings: 'The Flash' and 'NCIS' adjusted up, 'Chicago Fire' holds|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/10/14/tuesday-final-ratings-oct-13-2015/478601/|accessdate=October 14, 2015|wor